<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26270j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26270j">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26270j"> 270(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> epulum Jovis</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Eturia]</font>&mdash;Tradition always assigned to the last three kings of Rome a connection with the mysterious people of Etruria, and their influence at this period though not very definite was certainly extensive. To them <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> was due the introduction of Minerva, who, as the goddess of handicraft and protectress of the artisan gilds, was established in a temple on the Aventine. Soon, however, she found her way to the Capitol, and there a new Etruscan triad, Jupiter, Juno and Minerva, <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> was enshrined in a magnificent new temple <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> In this temple the deities were represented by images and on its dedication day, September 13th, at the novel festival of the <i><mark>epulum Jovis</mark></i>, the images were adorned and set out as partakers of the feast, a proceeding wholly foreign to the native Roman religion. <small> &ldquo;ROMAN RELIGION&rdquo; <a name="EBRR" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRR"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 579</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
